JEDSAD with MCRT: December Summary¶

This is a summary of the work I (James) have done on importing JEDSAD MHD wind models into a Monte Carlo radiative transfer code.

After initial testing with a model designed to roughly match Chakravorty et al. (2023), I've been seeing what one needs to do to get winds cold enough to produce optical features. Ideally, we'd be able to some weak blue-shifted absorption in lines like ${\rm H}\alpha$ and ${\rm He~I}~5876~{\rm A}$. For reference, here is a figure from Munoz-Darias et al. 2019 showing the absorption feature in the hard state.

Note that, in Koljonen et al. (2023) we got a reasonable match to the soft-state emission line spectrum using a parameterised biconical wind model, so we expect getting emission lines out of a wind model to be feasible for reasonable mass-loss rates. Absorption lines is less clear.

JEDSAD Model and System Parameters¶

Our JEDSAD solution is solN65. This has the following key parameters (see e.g. Jacquemin-Ide et al.:

  • Magnetisation $\mu = 0.0135$
  • Mass ejection index $p=0.163$

The file provided me gives the quantities like density, velocity, etc. along a streamline as a function of $y={\rm cotan} \theta= z/r$. I construct a 2D solution in the cylindrical $(r,z)$ or spherical $(R,\theta)$ plane by

  • 1- computing the $y$ from $y=z/r$
  • 2- interpolating on the value $F(y)$ in the provided column
  • 3- a given quantity $A$ like density is then given by a similarity relation: $$A= A(r_g) F(y) \left(\frac{r}{r_g}\right)^\beta$$

where $A(r_g)$ is the value at $r_g$ and the exponent depends on the variable. I've now checked the code that does this pretty carefully and after correcting a few errors I'm pretty confident its doing the 2D grid construction correctly.

The main other fixed parameters of the system are based on MAXI J1820 and are:

  • BH Mass, $M_{\rm BH} = 8.5 M_{\odot}$.
  • The illuminating SED (shape and normalisation).
  • the inner radius of the wind, $R_{\rm min}=10^3~r_g$. Note that I am assuming that the wind does actually extend further in, I'm just truncating it here in the models because I'm guessing the inner wind is very hot and unimportant in the optical (this turns out to be true).

I chose to vary two parameters here:

  • the outer wind radius, $R_{\rm max}$
  • the normalisation of the mass-loss, set through the parameter $\dot{m}$

The SED is shown in the next panel.

How to set $\dot{m}$¶

For a desired radiated Eddington fraction, assuming the wind runs right down to the ISCO, we have, from the definition of $\dot{m}$ used by Jonathan $$ \dot{m} = \frac{\dot{M}_{\rm acc} c^2}{L_{\rm Edd}} = \frac{\lambda_{\rm Edd}L_{\rm Edd} c^2}{\eta c^2 L_{\rm Edd}} = \frac{\lambda_{\rm Edd}}{\eta} $$ where we take $\eta=1/12$ as the radiative efficiency. For our SED we thus adopt $\dot{m} = 12 \times 0.214 = 2.575$ as the base, steady-state case. However, as Jonathan notes, the inner disc responds slowly to the outer disc, which could have a higher accretion rate and mass-loss rate. There is nothing simultaneous here, and shoud treat the two Mdot as independent (though related) quantities.

This for the moment, I simply try to vary $\dot{m}$ while keeping the SED fixed. I use values of $\dot{m}$ of 2.575, 8.137, and 25.75 (uniform in log space spanning one OOM).

Here are the results from five runs with different $\dot{m}$, $R_{\rm max}$.

Caveats¶

  • All of these models have the "wedge" below the ideal MHD point excised, but clearly this region is likely to be important for emission lines. However, it's unlikely to matter for blue-shifted absorption lines because it's not outflowing and will not cover the continuum source for most sightlines.
  • There is a heating prescription in the wind solutions, but it will not match the heating from the model. As such, there is an inconsistency here which could be "iterated" on (i.e. the heating from the RT simulations could be used to inform the prescription in the MHD solution).

 Plot Description¶

Each figure shows the following.

  • Top 4 panels: wind conditions in cylindrical coordinates. clockwise from top left, the convergence, log ionization parameter, log electron temperature, and log electron density in the wind.
  • 3rd row: the optical spectrum from 3000-7000A on a log-log scale (left), and a zoom in on the He I 5876A line to see if there are wind features.
  • 4th row, left: the "global" output SED. This is the emergent spectrum binned over all viewing angles over a broad wavelength range. The contribution of the input SED, the Wind reprocessing, and the total escaping spectrum is shown. Generally the wind starts to poke out above the input SED in the optical. The X-Shooter wavelength region is shaded.
  • 4th row, right: the $n_e-T_e$ "phase space" of the wind, colour-coded by log $H\beta$ luminosity. This shows where the emission is coming from in terms of physical conditions and how much cold material there is. In all cases there is hot material and dense material, but generally speaking cool gas at $10^4~{\rm K}$ is only present when $R_{\rm max}$ is large.

Summary of these results¶

Here is a quick summary of some of the main results from the above, in no particular order:

  • In massive winds the wind can have a big imprint on the emission line spectrum. Strong double-peaked emission lines are formed near the base of the wind - they are generally a little narrower than observed in 1820 but not far off. The width and strength depends strongly on $R_{\rm max}$ and $\dot{m}$.
  • In the dense models, the wind also has a significant reprocessing effect on the continuum and makes the optical-UV slope redder. This is pretty neat and arguably merits a study in and of itself. People typically associated the emission lines with the disk in some way, which is still reasonable in this model, but using the JEDSAD framework gives a physically motivated framework for a "disc atmosphere" or "wind transition region" to study. The results could feasibly change a fair bit if the "wedge" is included.
  • The dependence on $R_{\rm max}$ is pretty striking. Moving $R_{\rm max}$ out (to an unrealistically large value for MAXI J1820) means you get much more cool material which can emit recombination lines efficiently. Much of the inner wind is highly ionized.
  • The stratified ionization structure is interesting (although expected based on the gradients in ionizing flux and density in the flow), given the multi-phase wind signatures seen in X-ray binaries.
  • There are no obvious "wind absorption signatures" in the optical. Presumably this is just because the wind is not optically thick enough in the region where it is significantly outflowing. The obvious next step is to try even higher mass-loss rates, or clumping, or higher values of $p$ (mass ejection indices).
